<section xml:id="sec-dilations-Cartesian" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Scaling and Similarity</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
        In this section, we explore a type of transformation which changes the distance 
        between points. We begin by exploring some examples on the Cartesian
        <m>x,y</m>-plane. 
    </p>
    <!--<sidebyside widths="50% 45%">-->
        <p>
            To compute the length of a segment on a graph we use the Pythagorean 
            Theorem. In <xref ref="diag-seg-measure"/>, the coordinates of point <m>A</m> 
            are <m>(6,6)</m> and of point <m>B</m> are <m>(9,2)</m>. We find
            the horizontal distance between the two points by 
            subtracting the <m>x</m>-coordinates, <m>m(\overline{BC})=9-6 = 3</m>, 
            and the vertical distance by subtracting the <m>y</m>-coordinates, 
            <m>m(\overline{AC}=6-2 = 4</m>. Then since segment <m>\overline{AB}</m>
            is the hypotenuse of the right triangle <m>\Delta EFG</m>, we can use 
            the Pythagorean Theorem to find its length, namely 
            <m>m(\overline{EAB})=\sqrt{4^2+3^2}=\sqrt{9+16}=\sqrt{25}=5</m>.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="diag-seg-measure">
            <caption>Measuring distance on a graph</caption>
            <image source="Pythmeasure">
                <shortdescription>Right triange ABC described above.</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure>
    <!--</sidebyside>-->
    </introduction>    
    <subsection xml:id="subsec-scaling-Cartesian">
        <title>Magnifying Figures on a Cartesian <m>x,y</m>-Graph</title>
        <exploration>
            <task>
                <title>Constructing a Magnified Quadrilateral</title>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Use the either a printed copy or the GeoGebra applet 
                        of <xref ref="fig-scale-quad"/> to complete 
                        the following:
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Compute the lengths of the segment:
                                    <ol>
                                        <li>
                                            <m>\overline{AB}</m>
                                        </li>
                                        <li>
                                            <m>\overline{BC}</m>
                                        </li>
                                        <li>
                                            <m>\overline{CD}</m>
                                        </li>
                                        <li>
                                            <m>\overline{AD}</m>
                                        </li>
                                    </ol>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Measure the angles:
                                    <ol>
                                        <li>
                                            <m>\angle ABC</m>
                                        </li>
                                        <li>
                                            <m>\angle BCD</m>
                                        </li>
                                        <li>
                                            <m>\angle CDA</m>
                                        </li>
                                        <li>
                                            <m>\angle DAB</m>
                                        </li>
                                    </ol>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Multiply the coordinates of each vertex by
                                    2 to obtain coordinates for points <m>A'</m>, 
                                    <m>B'</m>, <m>C'</m>, and <m>D'</m>.
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    Then plot and connect the points to form quadrilateral
                                    <m>\quad A'B'C'D'</m>.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="fig-scale-quad">
                        <caption>GeoGebra app to scale a quadrilateral</caption>
                        <interactive xml:id="scale-quad-app"
                        platform="geogebra">
                        <slate surface="geogebra" material="njv9uaug"/>
                      </interactive>
                    </figure>
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task>
                <title>Relationships between the Image and the Original</title>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Refer to your work in <xref ref="fig-scale-quad"/> as you 
                        answer the following:
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Describe how the quadrilateral <m>A'B'C'D'</m>you drew in
                                    <xref ref="fig-scale-quad"/> relates to the original 
                                    quadrilateral <m>ABCD</m>.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Measure the new angles, <m>\angle A'B'C'</m>,
                                    <m>\angle B'C'D'</m>, <m>\angle C'D'A'</m>,
                                    and <m>D'A'B'</m>. How do they compare to the 
                                    original four angles?
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Compute the lengths of the following segments
                                    <ol>
                                        <li>
                                            <m>\overline{A'B'}</m>
                                        </li>
                                        <li>
                                            <m>\overline{B'C'}</m>
                                        </li>
                                        <li>
                                            <m>\overline{C'D'}</m>
                                        </li>
                                        <li>
                                            <m>\overline{A'D'}</m>
                                        </li>
                                    </ol>
                                    Compare these to the original side lengths.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Let <m>O</m> be the point <m>(0,0)</m>. 
                                    Draw the rays <m>\overrightarrow{OA'}</m>,
                                    <m>\overrightarrow{OB'}</m>, <m>\overrightarrow{OC'}</m>,
                                    and <m>\overrightarrow{OD'}</m>. What do you notice about 
                                    each of these rays?
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>  
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
        </exploration>
    </subsection> 
